			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2011</a> paper:</span><br><i>Design of Concept Libraries for C++</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AndrewMSutton.html">Andrew M. Sutton</a>, <a href="../profile/BjarneStroustrup.html">Bjarne Stroustrup</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_6">10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_6</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> C++ concepts are a static semantics/type system mechanism; the paper focuses on designing concept libraries.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1e.html"><span class="tagL">T1E: Reuse</span></a><ul><li> Concept libraries aim at reusable abstractions and constraints for generic programming.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagL">T3F: API</span></a><ul><li> The work is about library/API design patterns for specifying and consuming concepts.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL">T3D: GPLs</span></a><ul><li> C++ is a general purpose language.
</li></ul></li></ul>
